2. Fixes for NVIDIA + Vulkan on Arch
Run these in a terminal and report which ones change behavior:

A. Install Vulkan deps for NVIDIA
On Arch with an NVIDIA dGPU + Optimus (AMD iGPU), you need:

bash
sudo pacman -S \
    vulkan-icd-loader \
    lib32-vulkan-icd-loader \
    nvidia-utils \
    lib32-nvidia-utils \
    nvidia-prime
Then remove conflicting mesa‑based Vulkan drivers if you’re not using them:

bash
sudo pacman -Rdd amdvlk 2>/dev/null || true
sudo pacman -Rdd lib32-amdvlk 2>/dev/null || true
Many users fix the VK_KHR_surface error this way.

B. Force NVIDIA Vulkan in Steam
If you still see the error, start Steam with NVIDIA Vulkan explicitly:

bash
VK_ICD_FILENAMES=/usr/share/vulkan/icd.d/nvidia_icd.json prime-run steam
If that doesn’t work, try without prime‑run first to see which Vulkan driver is actually picked:

bash
vulkaninfo --summary
You should see your NVIDIA card; if it’s only AMD‑only, Vulkan is not routing to the NVIDIA ICD.

C. Check if Vulkan is at all working
Run:

bash
vkcube
If this crashes or says “no Vulkan device found”, then the system‑level Vulkan stack is broken; Steam will never initialize.

3. If you’re on a NVIDIA‑only desktop (no Optimus)
If this is not an Optimus laptop and you’re just using NVIDIA:

bash
sudo pacman -S nvidia-utils lib32-nvidia-utils vulkan-icd-loader lib32-vulkan-icd-loader
VK_ICD_FILENAMES=/usr/share/vulkan/icd.d/nvidia_icd.json steam
No prime‑run needed in that case.

4. Quick test to confirm Steam picks NVIDIA
Once Vulkan works (vkcube runs), check:

bash
VK_ICD_FILENAMES=/usr/share/vulkan/icd.d/nvidia_icd.json prime-run steam --no-xt
Then in Steam → Settings → About, it should show your NVIDIA GPU, not AMD Radeon Graphics (RADV RENOIR).
